She was never abused. She abused Johnny. So much proof to back it up.

Not going to say I agree or disagree with your statement. Albeit your argument is based on a skewed metric — your personal experience with abuse isn’t a litmus test for the whole. 
An example would be rape. Some women become promiscuous, while others refrain from intimacy. Some commit suicide or homicide. Some simply do not exhibit any changes at all. 
Therefore, if victim A became promiscuous, her argument would be that victim  B truly wasn’t raped because she didn’t exhibit the same outcome as she.
I personally believe she was abused. The question for justice is to ascertain to what extent. E.g. verbally, physically, emotionally — days, weeks, months, years?
Johnny Depp is known to be an addict to multiple vices. Such vices are known to cause aggression, mental instability, and loss of rationale. Furthermore, Johnny Depp lost an anti-defamation suite when he believed that he wasn’t an “abuser”. However, the courts didn’t find merit in his suit; allowing tabloids to label him as such. 
Justice is to ascertain what wrong was done, If any, and translate it to something equitable Whether monetary or penal. 
The judge here doesn’t deny abuse, what he is challenging is to what extent.
At this point, who isn’t an abuse survivor?
